{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":21398,"record_hash":"sha256:c2f437bbde6bda5ed6e74b26cffe5bdd24d673e0fe41f35ff3cfb7fa2b46559c","timestamp":"2026-05-10T20:50:55.317Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Closer, but not “ready to implement both” just because of `set_record` / `get_record`.\n\nThey help with one slice: **record-shaped scalar metadata**, especially source metadata like:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:source:<source-key>:agent\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:source:<source-key>:model\n```\n\nBut the two use cases need more than that.\n\n**What We Have Now**\nThe data shape is still good for both use cases:\n\n- durable project-scoped session keys\n- transcript list per session\n- redacted normalized fields for browsing/handoff\n- future branch/PR/change relationships as sets of session keys\n\n`get_record` makes reading source metadata nicer. It does **not** make the whole session readable as one record, because the session prefix also contains `sources` as a set and `transcript` as a list. That is fine; it just means an agentlog reader should compose several GitMeta reads.\n\n**Still Needed For Session Handoff**\nWe would need:\n\n- GitMeta exchange: serialize/fetch/push/sync or whatever transport flow GitMeta wants.\n- A `but-agentlog` read API:\n  ```rust\n  list_sessions(repo, target)\n  get_session(repo, target, session_key)\n  ```\n- A handoff format: probably a compact context stream derived from `role`, `content_text`, `tool_name`, `event_kind`, and selected `source_record`.\n- Agent-specific exporters/adapters: Claude handoff and Codex/OpenClaw handoff may not want the exact same shape.\n- UX for selecting the session when there are multiple project sessions.\n\n**Still Needed For Code Review Context**\nWe would need:\n\n- relationship writes from branch/change/commit/PR targets:\n  ```text\n  <review target>\n    gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n  ```\n- a reader that starts from that target, resolves session keys on `project`, and renders transcripts.\n- publishing/sync/privacy decisions before showing this on a GitButler website.\n- probably a summary/index later, because reading full transcripts for every PR view may get heavy.\n\n**My Recommendation**\nWe are in a good position to implement the **next internal layer**, not the full use cases.\n\nThe next sensible step would be a small read API inside `but-agentlog` that hides raw GitMeta keys:\n\n```rust\nlist_session_keys(repo, target)\nread_session(repo, target, session_key)\n```\n\nNo CLI, no web, no handoff yet. Just prove the stored shape is pleasant to read. That would tell us if we need more GitMeta API work, without committing to the product features too early.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-10T20:50:55.317Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}